    "id": "361",
    "title": "Emergency Heart Failure Mortality Risk Grade (EHMRG)",
    "desc": "The Emergency Heart Failure Mortality Risk Grade (EHMRG) estimates 7-day mortality of emergency CHF patients.",
    "data": {
        "orgreference": [
            {
                "href": "https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22665814",
                "text": "Lee DS, Stitt A, Austin PC, Stukel TA, Schull MJ, Chong A, Newton GE, Lee JS, Tu JV. Prediction of heart failure mortality in emergent care: a cohort study. Ann Intern Med. 2012 Jun 5;156(11):767-75, W-261, W-262. doi: 10.7326/0003-4819-156-11-201206050-00003. PubMed PMID: 22665814."
            }
        ],
        "other_refer": [],
        "evidence": "<p>Addition of the assigned points, with several definitions, ranges, and limits:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Age is multiplied &times; 2.</li>\n<li>Systolic blood pressure is subtracted (multiply &times; -1), with an upper limit of 160 mmHg.</li>\n<li>Heart rate is limited to rates between 80-120.</li>\n<li>Oxygen saturation is subtracted and doubled (multiply &times; -2), with an upper limit of 92%.</li>\n<li>'Troponin positive' is defined as greater than the upper limit of normal for one's laboratory.</li>\n<li>An adjustment factor of 12 points was added to this score to make the median score approach zero.</li>\n</ul>",
        "facts": "<ul>\n<li>As stated above, the Emergency Heart Failure Mortality Risk Group (EHMRG) score cannot be used in patients on dialysis.</li>\n<li>This score will be stronger with external validation, but the c-statistics were good for both the derivation and validation cohorts (0.803).</li>\n<li>Mortality trends were similar in patients both admitted to the hospital and discharged from the ED, but with lower rates of death for those patients who were admitted.</li>\n<li>The authors note that this interestingly does not include an ejection fraction in its calculation, and this may be a weakness of the study.</li>\n<li>This was derived from a Canadian population, where EMS usage may be different, as well as use of metolazone and heart failure management strategies compared to other countries.</li>\n</ul>",
